segments.text: I don't think that, I really don't think there should be any classes that size.
I could see it maybe having a very distinguished lecture and then having a whole bunch of teaching assistants take them into separate sections, but that's not the way it happens there.
They're in a class of 500 and then they have stand-up contests.
And I don't think this is fair.
So, more money needs to go into faculty and less into building.
I think we spend a lot of money on building.
And I was very glad to see a couple of years ago, or was it last year, that somebody decided simply that the money would go to the faculty.
It would not go anywhere else.
I want to see more of a place on teaching as something to be evaluated and to be a place to follow that forward.
I want to see fewer committees and less committee work, because I think the people now in the community club and anywhere that's involved in committee work, they don't have time to do it.
I'd like to see sabbaticals given more regularly and without complications.
And I think it would be the case that somebody would find a good job for X number of years and do the sabbaticals.
I think things would affect the whole.
How about the enrollment?
Yeah, I was just going to raise that issue.
An admission requirement.
I think that they should cap the enrollment.
They already have that, haven't they?
They have.
They say they have.
Raise the admission requirements.
Encourage rather than discourage out-of-state enrollment for students.
We're not going to have dozens, well, dozens, of course.
We're not going to have thousands and thousands of people walking in.
We're not going to be able to do that.
We're going to make it a little more open to people from Pennsylvania and California.
I think, too, that we should work with junior college systems to alleviate some of the fall-ins.
And we are doing some of that.
I know that we work with Glenn to alleviate the pressure on freshman students on technical writing.
And this is Bill.
What is your finding so far about the...
What is your finding so far about the...
quality of instruction that Glenn is giving?
Well, on the basic level, it's pretty much the same.
They're all our graduate students who are teaching here who are also teaching there.
Okay.
Who then, in some cases, graduate from here with their masters and go teach there full-time,
often because they're married to somebody here.
I don't think there's any problem with that.
They have worse students.
They've got some awful students over there.
And sometimes the awful students will get through the courses.
Just anybody who does all the work over there is going to get through.
Nobody's going to fail except people who don't, who disappear at midterm.
So we do get some people from Glenn that have high grades that aren't very good.
But I don't think that they're getting bad courses over there.
I think they're getting good courses.
And, in fact, I think they're getting essentially our courses.
I don't know.
How do you feel?
What is your thought about A&M Street here?
Why don't you...
We've done it.
It should go down to, let's say, no more than 35.
I don't know how to do this.
This is not...
But it would seem to be possible to do it.
And I think a lot of it is.
I read a lot of that document, and I thought, God.
Some of it is very good, but a lot of it is very vague, too.
I mean, we really need to have more instructors on all levels.
And we need to have, to be competitive with UT, we need to have a lot more instructors.
And that's in the report, but it's not specific to...
I'm using the word instructor, meaning anyone who teaches...
But I don't think that we can do it with...
For a while, we had many, many lectures.
I don't think this is a good idea because people who are really good instructors don't
generally want to be lifetime lecturers.
Lifetime lecturers... And we have a couple of lifetime lecturers who are excellent.
But we've had many, many people pass through here, some of whom were terrible.
So I think we need more tenure-track people.
And those lectures we do have, we need to treat well, and we need to make them senior
lecturers so that somebody, for instance, like Dorothy Van Ryber...
Have you spoken with her?
There's somebody... No.
No.
Well, she's a lifetime lecturer.
And she will tell you what this does.
Because she's teaching...
For a while.
For a while.
For a while.
For a while.
For a while.
For a while.
For a while.
For a while.
For a while.
For a while.
For a while.
For a while.
For a while.
For a while.
For a while.
For a while.
Because she's teaching essential classes, and yet, I think that there's a
kind of bitterness on the part of lifetime lecturers, because they're not...
And she is a senior lecturer, but we need to have better conditions for our lecturers.
Alright, any female-related experiences, plus and minus, that you want to share that
we haven't already done throughout all the years.
Female-related?
Yeah.
Okay.
Being a woman faculty member, the pluses or the minuses here?
Well, I can think of lots of little slights from the old days, but nothing major.
What about a positive?
Were you, okay, the thing has turned, the tide is going the positive way?
Being a female, I don't know.
I do remember that when I was having children, my students did not approve of this.
And one of them said to me, this is a negative experience, a core person said to me, I wouldn't
let my wife be pregnant and teach.
Here I was about eight months pregnant and I was teaching.
And I don't remember what I said to him.
I remember I looked at him in astonishment, but I don't remember, I don't think I had
any snappy comeback.
I think I just said, well, that's lovely for you and went on to something else.
But I encountered that quite a bit.
And it was kind of funny because there were a bunch of pregnant teachers in the English
department at once.
Pat Harris was in the department then and she was pregnant.
And there was a woman named Judy Finn who hasn't been around for years and years and
she was there.
And we kind of took up the whole faculty room.
But there was a certain amount of you shouldn't be here at that point that was not accepted.
I can't think of any really awful.
I never encountered.
And nor can I think of anything astoundingly wonderful that happened to me here because
I was a woman.
I've just always been here and I've always taught and I've become aware of the improvement
of attitudes towards women.
And as the years go by, there are more and more women.
There's less and less discrimination against them.
But there are still some Aggies who think.
If we could get all of the people from your A&M experience to come here and talk to you,
and to one place, to which ones and for what would you most want to express your appreciation?
To who?
Okay, Stanley Archer.
Because?
Because he guided me all these years.
He was one of the first people to, what, to recognize me as a faculty member as opposed
to another one of the teaching assistants.
Frank Pierce.
Because actually Frank was very protective during those years.
He was a very good teacher.
He was a very good teacher.
And he was one of the people that, for instance, back then you didn't have any choice about
where and when you taught ordinarily.
And they could just as soon send you a mile away.
But Frank Pierce was always, like when I was having children and so forth, he always made
sure my classes were relatively local and that they were at good hours.
And he also, he was the first person to say, we all, I called all these people doctor this
and that.
And Frank was the first person to say, call me Frank.
And I appreciated that.
Stanley Frank, Bedford Clark, but just, he's my long-term friend here.
I was here when they hired him, I think he was a great hire, he's always been around
for good advice.
Who else?
Don't have to be in the department now, anyone.
Oh, they don't have to be in the department.
Anyone associated with A&M that you.
Okay, Maxine Davenport, Manuel's first wife.
And Manuel himself.
Sylvia Grider, who also came in a long time ago and who has not contributed .
And he taught everybody much good, but he was very kind to me and very helpful.
And he made all kinds of dreadful mistakes with other people.
And he was best known for dragging in people to see the department had he let their plans
go by himself.
He was not winning any friends at all.
I was careful not to do that.
I did that when my class was anywhere in the vicinity of parks.
But he was very good to me.
And so I would remember him, I would go to him for advice.
You know, when I'm thinking, except for Sylvia, these are all men.
Catherine O'Keeffe is not here anymore.
She's at Notre Dame.
Well, we can go to her for advice.
I would want it for the establishment of an MFA program.
A million dollars wouldn't go far in that direction.
If I couldn't do that, then I wouldn't have.
This is very, very important.
Thank you.
It's been, it's been took so long now.
I've been here since 1958 and I've been teaching here since 1969.
I taught elsewhere before and for one year during the time period.
But other than that, I know nothing, I don't know how other institutions work.
And I certainly enjoyed teaching here.
I was still in college.
I'm still in contact with many students, some of them even going back, I'm not in contact with other people from that time period.
And now I'm beginning to see, I've had the children of my first student, I figure when the grandchildren show up, I'm probably going to retire.
So, I would say, in many ways, I do identify with Texas A&M a lot, but I'm not a traditional student.
Every elementary school student identifies with Texas A&M.
Okay, I'm just trying to think of things at the very beginning.
